{"slug": "amalgam", "root": "amalgam", "category": "alchemy", "gloss": "a mercury alloy; a blending", "definition": "An *amalgam* is an alloy formed by dissolving another metal — gold, silver, tin — into liquid mercury, yielding a soft, workable mass. Where ordinary alloys are fused in the fierce heat of the crucible, an amalgam forms almost cold, mercury swallowing its partner. The alchemists prized the gold amalgam as a step toward the philosophers' stone; the word later widened to any fusion of disparate things.", "history": "Medieval Latin *amalgama* — probably from Arabic *al-malgham*, 'emollient, soft mass' — names the pliant paste mercury makes when it takes up another metal, one more Arabic *al-* word smuggled into the science of metals. Alchemical writers kept it literal: the *Mutus Liber* speaks of the philosophic amalgam of mercury, gold and the silver of art. The turn is metaphorical and late: by the seventeenth century any blending of unlike elements — of doctrines, peoples, notions — could be called an amalgam, and scholars now write of Hermetism as an Hellenistic amalgam of Platonism, Stoicism, and Judaism.", "def_sources": [{"label": "McLean, A Commentary on the Mutus Liber", "where": "Alchemy (PDF)"}, {"label": "Zambelli, White Magic, Black Magic in the European Renaissance", "where": "Renaissance magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Etymonline, s.v. amalgam", "where": "Etymology reference"}], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"lang": "Arabic", "origin": "Medieval Latin amalgama, prob. from Arabic al-malgham 'emollient, soft mass'", "first": "c. 1400", "note": "A mercury alloy — and another Arabic al- word smuggled into science. 'Amalgamation' of ideas is a 17th-c. metaphor.", "hook": "One more Arabic 'al-' hiding in plain sight."}, "essay": null, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_